steps.text:
`onDidChangeSemanticTokens` is a refresh *notification*, not a guaranteed immediate call to `provideDocumentSemanticTokens`. VS Code coalesces refreshes and may suppress one while a request for the same document/version is already pending. That matches your debounce race: VS Code requests tokens after the edit before the server has processed it; the later `fire()` can be absorbed.

Also, subscribe to your custom event directly—don’t use `Function.call` as an event-registration wrapper:

```ts
RegisterOnSentTextEdits(callback: () => void): vscode.Disposable {
    return this.mOnSentTextEditsEvent(callback);
}

file_watcher.RegisterOnSentTextEdits(() => {
    semantic_highlighter_provider_instance.mOnDidChangeSemanticTokens.fire();
});
```

Expose the semantic event on the actual registered provider instance:

```ts
class SemanticProvider implements vscode.DocumentSemanticTokensProvider {
    private readonly _onDidChangeSemanticTokens =
        new vscode.EventEmitter<void>();

    readonly onDidChangeSemanticTokens =
        this._onDidChangeSemanticTokens.event;

    provideDocumentSemanticTokens(document, token) {
        // Return tokens for document.version currently processed by your server.
    }

    refresh() {
        this._onDidChangeSemanticTokens.fire();
    }
}
```

More importantly, make the provider version-aware. Track the document version sent to and acknowledged by your server; only return tokens when they correspond to the `document.version` passed to the provider. If they do not match, return no tokens and fire the refresh after the server reaches that version. Do not rely on `fire()` to force a distinct provider invocation for every edit.

The API explicitly describes the event only as signaling that tokens changed, not as a synchronous “call provider now” mechanism. [VS Code API reference](https://code.visualstudio.com/api/references/vscode-api#DocumentSemanticTokensProvider)
